Single cell RNA-seq data analysis

Introduction

In this section, you will go through the most basic steps for Single cell RNA seq analysis with R packages including:

Seurat package from Satija Lab et al dplyr package from Hadley Wickham et.al Matrix package from Douglas Bates et.al Matrix.utils package from Craig Varrichio ggplot2 package from Hadley Wickham et.al reshape2 package from Hadley Wickham pryr package from Hadley Wickham et.al RColorBrewer package from Erich Neuwirth And local source from genetic department of UMCG

Public data

Data used in this section is freely available from 10X Genomics, with 2700 single cells that were sequenced on the Illumina NextSeq 500 there is a link to data from website of Seurat

Loading data in Seurat

pbmc.data <- Read10X(data.dir = "./hg19")

QC and selecting cells for further analysis

# Initialize the Seurat object with the raw (non-normalized data).  Keep all

# genes expressed in >= 3 cells (~0.1% of the data). Keep all cells with at

# least 200 detected genes



pbmc <- CreateSeuratObject(raw.data = pbmc.data, min.cells = 3, min.genes = 200, 

                           project = "10X_PBMC")



# The number of genes and UMIs (nGene and nUMI) are automatically calculated

# for every object by Seurat.  For non-UMI data, nUMI represents the sum of

# the non-normalized values within a cell We calculate the percentage of

# mitochondrial genes here and store it in percent.mito using AddMetaData.

# We use object@raw.data since this represents non-transformed and

# non-log-normalized counts The % of UMI mapping to MT-genes is a common

# scRNA-seq QC metric.

mito.genes <- grep(pattern = "^MT-", x = rownames(x = pbmc@data), value = TRUE)

percent.mito <- Matrix::colSums(pbmc@raw.data[mito.genes, ])/Matrix::colSums(pbmc@raw.data)

# AddMetaData adds columns to object@meta.data, and is a great place to

# stash QC stats

pbmc <- AddMetaData(object = pbmc, metadata = percent.mito, col.name = "percent.mito")





VlnPlot(object = pbmc, features.plot = c("nGene", "nUMI", "percent.mito"), nCol = 3)

# We filter out cells that have unique gene counts over 2,500 or less than 200

# and cells with high "percent.mito" (>0.05)

#Note that low.thresholds and high.thresholds are used to define a

# 'gate'.  -Inf and Inf should be used if you don't want a lower or upper

# threshold.

pbmc <- FilterCells(object = pbmc, subset.names = c("nGene", "percent.mito"), 

                    low.thresholds = c(200, -Inf), high.thresholds = c(2500, 0.05))

##the numbers on the pictures are correlation coefficients

Question 1: Why it’s important to filter out cells with high unique gene counts?

Normalizing the data

By default, we employ a global-scaling normalization method “LogNormalize” that normalizes the gene expression measurements for each cell by the total expression, multiplies this by a scale factor (10,000 by default), and log-transforms the result

pbmc <- NormalizeData(object = pbmc, normalization.method = "LogNormalize", 

                      scale.factor = 10000)

Detection of variable genes across the single cells

genes with extremly low (0.0125) and high (3) mean expression value were removed genes with low variation (y.cutoff = 0.5) were removed

pbmc <- FindVariableGenes(object = pbmc, mean.function = ExpMean, dispersion.function = LogVMR, 

                          x.low.cutoff = 0.0125, x.high.cutoff = 3, y.cutoff = 0.5)

length(x = pbmc@var.genes)
## [1] 1838

Scaling the data and removing unwanted sources of variation

regress out unwanted sources (batch effect, cell cycle stage, detected molecules per cell, the percentage mitochondrial gene content et.al)

here we only regress out detected molecules per cell (nUMI) and the percentage mitochondrial gene content evaluated before.

pbmc <- ScaleData(object = pbmc, vars.to.regress = c("nUMI", "percent.mito"))

Cluster the cells

resolution need to be set and increased values leading to a greater number of clusters. 0.6-1.2 typically returns good results for single cell datasets of around 3K cells incease resolution when you have bigger datasets

pbmc <- FindClusters(object = pbmc, reduction.type = "pca", dims.use = 1:10, 

                     resolution = 0.6, print.output = 0, save.SNN = TRUE)

Question 3: Why t-SNE not PCA ?

Finding differentially expressed genes (cluster biomarkers)

# find all markers of cluster 1

cluster1.markers <- FindMarkers(object = pbmc, ident.1 = 1, min.pct = 0.25)

print(x = head(x = cluster1.markers, n = 5))





# find all markers distinguishing cluster 5 from clusters 0 and 3

cluster5.markers <- FindMarkers(object = pbmc, ident.1 = 5, ident.2 = c(0, 3), 

                                min.pct = 0.25)

print(x = head(x = cluster5.markers, n = 5))



#also we can perform a pair wise detection

#find markers distiguishing cluster 1 from cluster 2



cluster1_2.markers <- FindMarkers(object = pbmc, ident.1 = 1, ident.2 = 2, 

                                  min.pct = 0.25)

Now we want to find markers for every cluster

# find markers for every cluster compared to all remaining cells, report only the positive ones



pbmc.markers <- FindAllMarkers(object = pbmc, only.pos = TRUE, min.pct = 0.25, 

                               thresh.use = 0.25)



#could be slow



#print top 2 markers names each clusters

pbmc@ident <- plyr::mapvalues(x = pbmc@ident, from = current.cluster.ids, to = new.cluster.ids)

Answers

1: Cells with extremly high unique gene counts could be doublets with different cell types.

2: The object of downstream analysis is to identify cell types based on gene expression. So Things influence gene expression besides cell types should be regarded as unwanted sources, e.g. total expression values, cell viability, batch effect ……

3: In brief, t-SNE will consider the relationship between cells which is more good at presenting the differences between cell types, so it’s well applied in single cell visualization.
